To set up AWS EKS Pod Identity management, we need to create an IAM role with a specific trust relationship that allows the EKS Pod Identity service to assume the role. Then, we attach the necessary permissions (S3 Read-Only) and create the association between the IAM role and the Kubernetes service account within the EKS cluster.

Here is the complete Terraform configuration:

```hcl
# AWS Provider Configuration
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

# 1. Define the IAM Policy Document for EKS Pod Identity
# This policy allows the EKS Pod Identity service to assume the role and tag sessions
data "aws_iam_policy_document" "example" {
  statement {
    effect = "Allow"

    principals {
      type        = "Service"
      identifiers = ["pods.eks.amazonaws.com"]
    }

    actions = [
      "sts:AssumeRole",
      "sts:TagSession"
    ]
  }
}

# 2. Create the IAM Role using the trust policy defined above
resource "aws_iam_role" "example" {
  name               = "example-eks-pod-identity-role"
  assume_role_policy = data.aws_iam_policy_document.example.json
}

# 3. Attach the S3 Read-Only Access managed policy to the role
resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "example_s3_readonly" {
  policy_arn = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess"
  role       = aws_iam_role.example.name
}

# 4. Define the EKS Pod Identity Association
# This links the IAM role to a specific EKS cluster, namespace, and service account
resource "aws_eks_pod_identity_association" "example" {
  cluster_name    = "example"
  namespace       = "default"
  service_account = "example-service-account"
  role_arn        = aws_iam_role.example.arn
}
