response:
To create a public NAT Gateway in AWS using Terraform, we need to define the `aws_nat_gateway` resource. This resource requires an Elastic IP (EIP) allocation ID and the ID of the public subnet where the gateway will reside. Per your requirements, we will also apply the specific tag for identification.

Here is the complete Terraform configuration:

```hcl
# Provider configuration for AWS
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

# Variable definitions for flexibility
variable "subnet_id" {
  description = "The ID of the subnet in which to place the NAT Gateway"
  type        = string
}

variable "allocation_id" {
  description = "The Allocation ID of the Elastic IP address for the NAT Gateway"
  type        = string
}

# Resource definition for the AWS NAT Gateway
resource "aws_nat_gateway" "this" {
  # The Allocation ID of the Elastic IP address for the gateway
  allocation_id = var.allocation_id

  # The Subnet ID of the subnet in which to place the gateway
  subnet_id = var.subnet_id

  # Connectivity type defaults to "public" when an allocation_id is provided
  connectivity_type = "public"

  # Resource tags as requested
  tags = {
    pike = "permissions"
  }

  # It is a best practice to ensure the Internet Gateway is available 
  # before the NAT Gateway is created, though not strictly required in this standalone block.
}

# Output the NAT Gateway ID
output "nat_gateway_id" {
  value       = aws_nat_gateway.this.id
  description = "The ID of the NAT Gateway"
}
```

